Analysis of missing values

This is a superficial analysis of the missing values in the dataset. In an exam context it is not expected that you do this, but I wanted to include this here so that you familiarize yourselves with some of the usual metrics.

The first thing we are going to do is create a variable with the number of rows in the dataset. For this, we can use the function nrow()

# count number of rows
nrows <- sf_police %>% nrow()
nrows
[1] 133207

The syntax below computes the number of missing value in each column. It is not expected that you are able to do this in an exam context, since you have not had a formal course covering R in detail. However, I want to show you the code to perform this quick analysis.

Essentially, we are goint to use the function summarise() in a somewhat different manner as what we have done so far.

  • First of all, we are not going to perform any grouping prior to summarise().
  • Secondly, we are going to use the special dplyr function across(). This function enables us to apply functions over the specified columns. In these case over all column - specified by .cols = everything() -. We are only going to apply one function (.fns = function(x) sum(is.na(x))), but we could specify a list of functions. This function essentially sums the number of NAs in every column.

If you google or ask a chatbot of your choice how to do this, you will see there are many alternatives to compute the number of NAs in each column. Here I have chosen the dplyr syntax, which is the one you are most familiar with and the one I would like to remain consistent with throughout the course:

missing_vals1 <- 
sf_police %>% 
  summarise(
            across(
                # Apply accross every column
                .cols = everything(), 
                
                # Specify function is.na() to be applied to every column
                .fns = function(x) sum(is.na(x))
            )
  )

The result is a dataframe with the same columns as the original dataframe and a single row indicating the number of NAs in that specific column. However, we want the dataframe in a two column format:

  • One column to indicate the name of the column in the original dataset.
  • One column to indicate the corresponding number of NAs

To get the dataframe in this format, we will use pivot_longer(), as we have done in some of the examples: * with cols = everything() we specify that we want to pivot every column. * with names_to = "column" we indicate a categorical variable which will signal the column name of the corresponding value. * with values_to = "NAs" we indicate the name of the column to contain the values we are pivoting.

This is probably better understood checking the output:

missing_vals2 <- 
  missing_vals1 %>%
  pivot_longer(
    cols = everything(),
    names_to = "column",
    values_to = "NAs"
  )

Some additional variables: tod, month, month_day and year_week

  • month: month of the incident.
  • month_fday: first day of the month
  • month_day: day of the month.
  • week: calendar week of the incident.
  • tod: time of the day (morning, afternoon, evening, night).
    • This variable will divide the day in morning, afternoon, evening or night depending on the hour of the incident. For this we will use the function case_when(). In the exam, it is not expected that you have this level of command of R given that you have not had a formal course in R. That is why I am creating the variable for you.
      • The function hms() computes a time object from the specified string.
      • The function case_when() enables us to create a column with different values depending on logical conditions. In this case we are going to specify different time ranges for each time of the day.
sf_police <- 
sf_police %>% 
  # head(10) %>%
  mutate(
    tod = case_when(
            `Incident Time` >= hms("06:00:00") & 
            `Incident Time` <  hms("12:00:00")   ~ "morning",
            `Incident Time` >= hms("12:00:00") & 
            `Incident Time` < hms("18:00:00")   ~ "afternoon",
            `Incident Time` >= hms("18:00:00") & 
            `Incident Time` < hms("23:59:59")   ~ "evening",
            `Incident Time` >= hms("00:00:00") & 
            `Incident Time` < hms("06:00:00")   ~ "night",
          ),
    month = month(`Incident Date`, label = TRUE, abbr = FALSE),
    month_day = mday(`Incident Date`),
    month_fday = make_date(`Incident Year`, month),
    week = epiweek(`Incident Date`)
  ) %>% 
  
  # Place the created columns at the beginning of the dataframe
  select(`Incident Year`, month, month_fday, month_day, week, tod, everything()) %>% 
  
  # Order from most recent to olderst incident
  arrange(desc(`Incident Date`))

BP.2

Produce the same barplot as in barplot 1. but this time order the bars from highest to lowest.

  • HINT: you need to use the function factor() to turn the variable Police Districts into a factor variable.
  • HINT: to find the appropriate order for the districts, you need to compute an aux dataset that counts the number of incidents in every district. For this:
    • Use group_by() + summarize() in combination with the function n(), which counts the number of rows in each group (in this case, the number of inciudents).
    • Arrange this result from largest to smallest number of incidents using arrange() and desc()
    • The notes on the basics of R explain how to use group_by(), summarize(), arrange() and desc().
    • If you need help to use n(), google how to use the function n() in R.
  • HINT: to produce the factor variable, use factor(). As an example, see the notebook 03 on graph customization, which contains a specific section on how to create factor variables for the purpose of ensuring the proper order of the levels in a graph.

aux <-

Scatterplots

Group the dataset by Analysis Neighborhood and compute, for each neighborhood:

  • The total number of incidents using n(). Call it n_incidents
  • The mean() latitude of every incident in the neighborhood. Call it mean_latitude. This will be used as a representative latitude of the neighborhood.
  • The mean() longitude of every incident in the neighborhood. Call it mean_longitude. This will be used as a representative longitude of the neighborhood.

Create one scatterplot for latitude vs. n_incidents and one for longitude vs. n_incidents. Is there a strong correlation between the number of incidents and either the latitude or the longitude?

aux <- 
  sf_police %>% 
  group_by(`Analysis Neighborhood`) %>% 
  summarize(
    n_incidents = n(),
    mean_latitude = mean(Latitude, na.rm = TRUE),

LP. 1

We want to create lineplots of the number of incidents in each month over time for the different police districts (variable Police District).

For this:

  1. group_by() the variables Police District and month_fday.
  2. summarize() using the function n() to count the number of rows in each group (corresponding to the number of incidents in a district within a given month). Name this variable n_incidents.
  3. ungroup() the result and store the result in an auxiliary variable aux.
  4. Use this aux dataset to produce the graph below:
    • HINT: use scale_x_date(breaks = "1 month", minor_breaks = "1 month") to scale the x-axis accordingly.

The desired dataset structure is shown below:

aux <- 
sf_police %>% 
  group_by(`Police District`, month_fday) %>% 
  summarize(
    n_incidents = n()
  ) %>% 
  ungroup()
`summarise()` has grouped output by 'Police District'. You can override using
the `.groups` argument.

LP. 2 - important geom_step().

Starting from the aux dataset of the previous exercise, we are going to (code for this given below):

  1. arrange() by both Police District and month_fday. This ensures that we have the observations within each Police District ordered chronologically.
  2. group_by() again by both Police District.
  3. Use mutate() and the function cumsum() to compute the cummulated number of incidents in each district as time progresses.
    • NOTE: we use group_by() + mutate() and not group_by() + summarize() because we want to preserve the number of rows in the dataset, yet want to perform the computation groupwise (we want the cummulative sum to be reset everytime the district changes).
    • Be sure to understand this. Check notebooks 00_B_1_tibbles_fundamentals and 00_B_group_by_examples and its associated .pdf file if you do not understand this.
# IMPORTANT NOTE:
# The variable aux is assumed to be the aux dataframe produced
# for exercise LP.1. 
# If this is not the case the code will not work properly.

aux2 <- 
  aux %>% 
  
    # Order the observations within each Police District
    # chronologically
    arrange(`Police District`, month_fday) %>%
  
    # Compute the cummulative sum of incidents for each
    # district
    group_by(`Police District`) %>% 
    mutate(
      cumul_incidents = cumsum(n_incidents)
    )

aux2

Use aux2 to produce the graph below. Importantly, use geom_step() and not geom_line() to generate this graph. The arguments and options are the same for both functions, just change the geom type.

aux2 %>% 
  
  ggplot(aes(x = month_fday, y = cumul_incidents, color = `Police District`)) +
  
  geom_step() +
  
  scale_x_date(breaks = "1 month", minor_breaks = "1 month") +
  
  theme(axis.text.x=element_text(angle = 90))

QUESTION why is this graph more appropriate to depict the cummulative sum over time?

geom_step() is better for cummulative sums and similar variables than geom_line()
because its shape when applied to this kind of cummulative data clearly signals
that we are performing a cummulative sum in which the value of the sum is an
aggregation over the entire month.

If we used geom_line instead it would appear that the cummulated incidents 
increase linearly within each month, which is not the case. See the graph below
aux2 %>% 
  
  ggplot(aes(x = month_fday, y = cumul_incidents, color = `Police District`)) +
  
  geom_line() +
  
  scale_x_date(breaks = "1 month", minor_breaks = "1 month") +
  
  theme(axis.text.x=element_text(angle = 90))

BoxP. 1 - somewhat advanced

For this code, I am going to provide a description of the data transformation operations as well as the associated code. It is part of the exercise that you understand this code in detail. Please ask any question you have about this entire code.

First, we identify which are the 5 worst and 5 best neighbourhoods in terms of total number of incidents. For this:

  1. filter() the dataset to eliminate rows with value NA (no data) in the variable Analysis Neighborhood-
  2. group_by() using the variable Analysis Neighborhood.
  3. Compute the total number of incidents (n_incidents) in each neighborhood counting the number of rows within each of those groups, using the function summarize() in combination with n()
  4. Store that intermediate result in a variable called aux.
  5. Order aux by descending n_incidents using arrange and retain only the first 10 rows. We can do this, for example, using the function head() with argument 10 (head(10)). If you need to, look on google how to use the function head(). Store this result as aux2.
    • Example with a dataframe df: df %>% head(5)
  6. Extract the column Analysis Neighborhood from aux2 and store it in a new variable called worst_nh. Note that this variable is a vector.
    • If you do not know how to do this check notebook 00_B_tibbles_dplyr_fundamentals, specifically how to pull a single variable from a tibble/dataframe.
  7. Filter the dataset sf_police to contain only obervations from the neighborhoods in worst_nh.
  8. Compute the number of incidents in each combination of Analysis Neighborhood and week using group_by, summarize and n().
  9. Redefine the variable Analysis Neighborhood so that it is a factor variable ordered following the list of worst neighborhoods worst_nh. For this you need to use mutate() and factor().
    • If you do not know how to do this, check notebook 03_ggplot_customizing.
  • HINT: see the sessions on R basics to see how to use arrange() and desc().
  • HINT: see the sessions on the basics of R to see how to extract a column from a tibble and store it in vector form.
aux <- 
  
  sf_police %>% 
  
  # Remove rows with NAs in the column Analysis Neighborhood
  filter(!is.na(`Analysis Neighborhood`)) %>% 
  
  # Compute number of incidents in each neighborhood
  group_by(`Analysis Neighborhood`) %>% 
  summarize(
    n_incidents = n()
  )
aux2 <- 
  aux %>% 
  
  # Order from largest to smallest n_incidents 
  arrange(desc(n_incidents))

aux3 <- 
  sf_police %>% 
    
    # Incidents only on 10 worst neighborhoods
    filter(
      (`Analysis Neighborhood` %in% worst_nh)
    ) %>% 
    
    # group by neighborhood and week of the incident
    # We wanto to count the number of incidents during each
    # week in each neighborhood
    group_by(`Analysis Neighborhood`, week) %>% 
    
    # count the number of incidents within each group
    summarize(
      n_inc_week = n()
    ) %>% 
  
    # Remove grouping so that operations are not performed groupwise
    ungroup() %>% 
  
    # Create a new factor variable to ensure proper ordering
    # of the neighborhoods
    mutate(
      `Analysis Neighborhood` = factor(`Analysis Neighborhood`,
                                       levels = worst_nh
                                      )
    )
`summarise()` has grouped output by 'Analysis Neighborhood'. You can override
using the `.groups` argument.

Using aux3, produce the following graph:

aux3 %>% 

  ggplot(aes(x = `Analysis Neighborhood`, y = n_inc_week)) +
  
  geom_boxplot()  +
  
  theme(axis.text.x=element_text(angle = 90))

QUESTION use that graph to indicate which of the 10 worst neighborhoods are similar/could be grouped together in terms of weekly incidents. Reason your answer based on the graph above… median values… inter-quantile ranges… spread of the data…

We can clearly see three different groups in terms of the weekly
incidents.

Within each of these groups, the median of the weekly incidents is
within the interquartile range of the distribution of weekly incidents
in the other neighborhoods.

The exception to this is the group with the lowest median weekly incidents,
where the neighbor North Beach exhibits a median value of weelky incidents
that is a little bit outside the IQR of the other neighborhoods. Specific
analysis could be performed to see if this difference is statistically
significant and, perhaps most importantly, whether it is relevant in terms
of the research being performed.
